n`)\n193: - `android-analysis/screen-map.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\screen-map.json`)\n194: - `android-analysis/view-bindings.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\view-bindings.json`)\n195: - `android-analysis/layout-tree.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\layout-tree.json`)\n196: - `android-analysis/drawable-semantics.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\drawable-semantics.json`)\n197: - `android-analysis/adapter-map.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\adapter-map.json`)\n198: - `android-analysis/data-schema.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\data-schema.json`)\n199: - `android-analysis/crud-slices.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\crud-slices.json`)\n200: - `android-analysis/backend-api-usage.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\backend-api-usage.json`)\n201: - `android-analysis/room-schema.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\room-schema.json`)\n202: - `android-analysis/retrofit-endpoints.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\retrofit-endpoints.json`)\n203: - `android-analysis/sqlite-schema.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\sqlite-schema.json`)\n204: - `android-analysis/preferences-map.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\preferences-map.json`)\n205: - `android-analysis/refresh-chains.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\refresh-chains.json`)\n206: - `android-analysis/aggregate-semantics.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\aggregate-semantics.json`)\n207: - `android-analysis/method-summaries.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\method-summaries.json`)\n208: - `android-analysis/data-flow-gaps.json`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\data-flow-gaps.json`)\n209: - `android-analysis/behavior-spec.md`: present (`D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\android-analysis\\behavior-spec.md`)\n210: \n211: If an input is missing, do not invent its contents. Fall back to source inspection only for the evidence needed by the current task, and report the gap.\n212: \n213: Treat Kotlin source, Gradle metadata, Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, resources, navigation, and user-visible refresh behavior as behavior evidence. Do not translate only UI skeletons; preserve search, filtering, CRUD, persistence, selection, dialogs, bottom bars, and immediate UI update semantics.\n214: \n215: Coverage reports are a baseline for reducing functional gaps and unexplained code-scale gaps. Do not mechanically match source LoC. Instead, map current-scope critical/high source features, resources, tests, and platform integrations to target implementation, supplemental tests, platform replacement, or explicit deferred items. `source-coverage-matrix.json` is the feature status record and `platform-capability-check.json` is the target platform capability status record: use both during planning and update them during phase/repair work. The main planning session should prioritize valid `plan.md` and `plan.json`; row-level `plannedPhase` backfill may be applied by a separate post-planning records-only session after the plan contract passes. Use language-specific static analysis outputs to refine the matrix when present. If static analysis reveals a source feature missing from the matrix template, add a matrix entry with source evidence. Critical/high `implemented` entries need specific evidence: do not bulk-promote many rows with the same notes/tests/endpoints, do not rely only on root views, shell views, state classes, whole files, or grouped endpoint lists, and do not cite target tests as strong evidence unless the notes record a successful target test compile/run command. For every closed critical/high feature, record `sourceBehavior`, `targetBehavior`, `parityLevel`, and `verificationEvidence` in `source-coverage-matrix.json`; `implemented` should use `parityLevel: equivalent`, `implemented-simplified` should use `parityLevel: simplified`, and `platform-replaced` should use `parityLevel: platform-replaced`. `verification-results.json/md` is generated evidence from build/test/manual reports, but a build pass alone is not per-feature behavior verification. Critical/high `implemented-simplified` is exceptional: record what was simplified, why user-visible behavior remains acceptable, target endpoints or tests, and source/platform evidence. Critical/high deferred feat... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n216: \n217: For this workflow, direct target API evidence means the capability is callable\n218: from the HarmonyOS Cangjie target. ArkTS `.d.ts` declarations, JS APIs, native C\n219: headers/libraries, or generic HarmonyOS capability docs are useful discovery\n220: evidence, but they are not direct Cangjie evidence by themselves. If only\n221: ArkTS/native bindings are found, record the missing Cangjie binding as a\n222: concrete blocker with fallback/deferred behavior unless a Cangjie wrapper, FFI,\n223: or bridge is already part of the target architecture or explicitly planned and\n224: verified with target endpoints plus build evidence. Do not introduce the first\n225: ArkTS/JS/native bridge merely to close coverage or capability rows, and do not\n226: mark a capability `verified-direct` or upgrade a feature to equivalent solely\n227: from ArkTS/native evidence.\n228: \n229: When checking current SDK availability, search pure Cangjie declarations first:\n230: `$HOME/.cangjie-sdk/**/cangjie/api/modules` for `.cj.d` files and\n231: `$HOME/.cangjie-sdk/**/cangjie/api/lib` for matching `.cjo` libraries. Treat\n232: DevEco ETS/JS/native SDK files as secondary discovery evidence unless a\n233: Cangjie-callable binding is found or already belongs to the target architecture.\n234: \n235: Static analysis is implementation evidence, not just matrix evidence. Use it during planning to decide phase boundaries, source evidence, files/assets/dependencies, state/data flow, platform replacement points, and test strategy. Use it during phase work to locate source behavior and preserve view/page bindings, event handlers, CRUD/persistence/API paths, refresh chains, schemas, resources, tests, and user-visible side effects. Use it during build or coverage repair to avoid deleting source-covered behavior merely to satisfy the compiler. When static analysis is incomplete or conflicts with source code, inspect the minimal relevant source files and follow the source code.\n236: \n237: Deferred is a last resort, not a planning shortcut. Do not mark features deferred merely because they are large, tedious, or inconvenient for compilation. Prefer faithful implementation; if exact parity is impossible, use the closest working implementation that preserves user-visible behavior and records the simplification reason; if platform capability differs, use a real HarmonyOS/Cangjie replacement. Use fallback or deferred only when a concrete blocker remains, such as unavailable HarmonyOS/Cangjie SDK capability, external service credentials, hardware/device dependency, legal/security constraint, or human product decision. Avoid bulk-deferred entries with repeated generic reasons.\n238: \n239: For ArkTS projects, prefer `arkts-analysis/compiler-summary.json`, `arkts-analysis/compiler-planning-note.md`, and phase-relevant compiler sidecars such as `compiler/behavior-spec.md`, `compiler/refresh-chains.json`, `compiler/method-summaries.json`, and `compiler/artifacts/cangjie-mapping-hints.json` before opening the full `arkts-analysis/compiler/analysis.json`.\n240: \n241: ## Static Analysis Limits\n242: \n243: Generated static analysis inputs are aids, not complete truth. They may miss dynamic dispatch, reflection, generated code, callback wiring, resource indirection, build-variant behavior, or platform-specific side effects. Do not rely only on static analysis when source behavior is unclear or when coverage reports indicate possible omissions. Inspect the minimal relevant source files and resources before deciding to simplify, replace, or defer behavior. For Kotlin projects, pay particular attention to Compose state, remembered state, ViewModel/repository flow, coroutine side effects, navigation arguments, and resource bindings that may be missing or only partially summarized.\n244: \n245: ## Target Architecture Organization\n246: \n247: Use the source project structure as a responsibility guide, then adapt it to\n248: idiomatic HarmonyOS Cangjie modules. Do not mechanically mirror Android\n249: Activity, Fragment, Adapter, BroadcastReceiver, ContentProvider, or XML layout\n250: boundaries, but also do not collapse unrelated domain behavior into broad files\n251: such as `index.cj`, `app_state.cj`, or one all-purpose state module. If\n252: source behavior is scattered only because of Android framework glue, lifecycle,\n253: binding, or layout boundaries, merge it into clearer Cangjie modules when that\n254: improves readability and repairability. Keep single-file LOC and responsibility\n255: scope controlled, and organize production Cangjie code around source business\n256: concepts such as domain models, repositories, data/storage services,\n257: commands/mutations, preferences/security or configuration services, state\n258: stores, and page composition. Thin UIAbility/page shell files may compose these\n259: modules, but they\n260: should not own repository, persistence, security, or mutation logic. For\n261: critical/high coverage entries, prefer targetEndpoints that identify precise\n262: modules or functions instead of only root views, whole files, or grouped state\n263: surfaces.\n264: \n265: ## Coverage And Capability Review\n266: \n267: Use `source-coverage-matrix.json/md` as the feature coverage record and `platform-capability-check.json/md` as the platform capability record. During planning and phase work, update them when target behavior is planned, implemented, tested, replaced, or explicitly deferred. Keep structured `coverageFacts` and `capabilityFacts` aligned with any legacy status/evidence fields you touch. The workflow uses these facts for phase gates, group verdicts, repair queues, and authority validation; explanatory prose is auxiliary and should not be the only place where a required fact appears. For every closed critical/high source feature, record sourceBehavior, targetBehavior, parityLevel, targetEndpoints, and verificationEvidence; use `verification-results.json/md` as supporting evidence, but do not treat a build pass alone as per-feature behavior verification. Avoid marking large groups of behavior deferred or implemented-simplified without concrete source evidence, preserved-behavior explanation, blocker reason, fallback behavior, risk, and future completion path. For critical/high platform capabilities, query CangjieSkills/HarmonyOS/Cangjie API docs and HarmonyOS-Examples before choosing a direct API, platform replacement, fallback, or deferred status. When a third-party package may be needed, also query the Cangjie package index (`https://pkg.cangjie-lang.cn`) or cjpm package lookup. When checking current SDK availability, prefer pure Cangjie `.cj.d`/`.cjo` declarations under `$HOME/.cangjie-sdk/**/cangjie/api/modules` and `$HOME/.cangjie-sdk/**/cangjie/api/lib` before DevEco ETS/JS/native declarations. If a suitable HarmonyOS/Cangjie API, Kit, example, or package exists, implement it or mark it platform-replaced with evidence; do not close the capability with local mock data, in-memory simulation, sample data, or another fallback. Direct target API evidence must be callable from the HarmonyOS Cangjie target. Treat ArkTS `.d.ts` declarations, JS APIs, native C headers/librar... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n268: \n269: ## Strict Coverage Task\n270: \n271: Do not silently omit, stub, or weaken source behavior. Every critical/high feature, resource, platform capability, test obligation, and Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, coroutine effects path must be implemented, replaced with a justified fallback, or documented as deferred with evidence and risk. Critical/high `implemented-simplified` entries must explain the simplification, preserved user-visible behavior, target endpoint/test evidence, source or platform evidence, parityLevel, targetBehavior, and verificationEvidence.\n272: \n273: ## Source Test Inventory\n274: \n275: The runner found these likely source-side tests or verification assets by path scan:\n276: \n277: - `app/src/androidTest/` (directory)\n278: - `app/src/test/` (directory)\n279: - `app/src/androidTest/java/` (directory)\n280: - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/` (directory)\n281: - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/example/` (directory)\n282: - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/example/foodike/` (directory)\n283: - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/example/foodike/ExampleInstrumentedTest.kt` (file)\n284: - `app/src/test/java/` (directory)\n285: - `app/src/test/java/com/` (directory)\n286: - `app/src/test/java/com/example/` (directory)\n287: - `app/src/test/java/com/example/foodike/` (directory)\n288: - `app/src/test/java/com/example/foodike/ExampleUnitTest.kt` (file)\n289: \n290: Use this inventory as a starting point. It can miss project-specific verification assets, so still inspect the source project during planning before deciding that tests are absent.\n291: \n292: ## Phase 1: Planning\n293: \n294: Generate detailed translation plans:\n295: \n296: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md`: human-readable phase plan, migration strategy, risks, gate criteria, and deferred items.\n297: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json`: strict JSON structured file, asset, dependency, phase, test, state-machine, group contract, and deferred-item plan.\n298: \n299: Use `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/plan-seed.md` / `.json` as the compact cross-language planning index when present. It summarizes source units, callable method/function/composable/event-handler contracts, UI route/action/state contracts, data/resource/platform capability contracts, phase/group candidates, structure risks, and analysis gaps from Java, Kotlin, mixed Android, or ArkTS inputs. Treat it as planning evidence, not a complete source of truth: inspect source files when behavior is unclear or when source code contradicts static analysis.\n300: \n301: The plan must include `files`, `assets`, `dependencies`, `tests`, `phases`, and `deferred`. For each phase, include canonical phase id, target scope, source evidence, gate command, expected tests, state/data behavior to preserve, and deferred risks. Each phase should also include implementation-group ownership data, either under `implementationGroups` inside the phase or in an equivalent top-level group map. Each group should include stable `groupId`, `title`, `groupType`, `priority`, `sourcePaths`, `sourceMethods` or callable contract references when available, `featureIds`, `resourceInputs`, `platformCapabilityIds`, `uiContracts` or UI route/action/state hints, `dataContracts`, `expectedTargetDomains`, `requiredBehaviors`, `riskHints`, and `acceptanceEvidence`. If static analysis misses or misstates behavior, record an `analysisGaps` or `sourceOverrides` note instead of silently dropping the behavior.\n302: \n303: ## Plan JSON Contract\n304: \n305: `plan.json` must be strict JSON and must include these required top-level keys:\n306: \n307: - `files`\n308: - `assets`\n309: - `dependencies`\n310: - `tests`\n311: - `phases`\n312: - `deferred`\n313: \n314: Extra top-level keys are allowed, but they do not replace the required keys. For\n315: example, `testStrategy` may provide detail, but `tests` must still exist.\n316: Likewise, `platformCapabilityDecisions` may provide detail, but\n317: `dependencies`, `assets`, and `deferred` must still exist when relevant.\n318: \n319: Minimum valid skeleton:\n320: \n321: ```json\n322: {\n323:   \"files\": [],\n324:   \"assets\": [],\n325:   \"dependencies\": [],\n326:   \"tests\": [],\n327:   \"phases\": [\n328:     {\n329:       \"id\": \"phase-01-project-skeleton-resources\",\n330:       \"title\": \"Project skeleton and resources\",\n331:       \"priority\": \"critical\",\n332:       \"targetScope\": [],\n333:       \"sourceEvidence\": [],\n334:       \"requiredInputs\": [],\n335:       \"expectedFiles\": [],\n336:       \"gateCommand\": \"\",\n337:       \"expectedTests\": [],\n338:       \"stateDataBehavior\": [],\n339:       \"deferredRisks\": [],\n340:       \"implementationGroups\": [\n341:         {\n342:           \"groupId\": \"phase-01-bootstrap\",\n343:           \"title\": \"Bootstrap target project\",\n344:           \"groupType\": \"source-behavior\",\n345:           \"priority\": \"critical\",\n346:           \"sourcePaths\": [],\n347:           \"sourceMethods\": [],\n348:           \"featureIds\": [],\n349:           \"resourceInputs\": [],\n350:           \"platformCapabilityIds\": [],\n351:           \"uiContracts\": [],\n352:           \"dataContracts\": [],\n353:           \"expectedTargetDomains\": [],\n354:           \"requiredBehaviors\": [],\n355:           \"riskHints\": [],\n356:           \"acceptanceEvidence\": []\n357:         }\n358:       ]\n359:     }\n360:   ],\n361:   \"deferred\": []\n362: }\n363: ```\n364: \n365: Use canonical phase identifiers such as `phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`.\n366: Each implementation group needs a stable `groupId`, `title`, `groupType`, and\n367: `priority`; bind it to source behavior, resources, capabilities, UI/data\n368: contracts, tests, or acceptance evidence whenever available. If the plan is\n369: large, write this complete valid skeleton first, then expand it in batches while\n370: keeping the file valid strict JSON after every write.\n371: \n372: \n373: Before ending the planning session, validate the planning artifacts with the\n374: platform-appropriate command below:\n375: \n376: POSIX shell:\n377: \n378: ```sh\n379: test -s 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md' && \\\n380:   test -s 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json' && \\\n381:   'C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe' -m json.tool 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json' >/dev/null\n382: ```\n383: \n384: Windows PowerShell:\n385: \n386: ```powershell\n387: if (!(Test-Path -LiteralPath 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md' -PathType Leaf)) { exit 1 }\n388: if ((Get-Item -LiteralPath 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md').Length -eq 0) { exit 1 }\n389: if (!(Test-Path -LiteralPath 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json' -PathType Leaf)) { exit 1 }\n390: if ((Get-Item -LiteralPath 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json').Length -eq 0) { exit 1 }\n391: & 'C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe' '-m' 'json.tool' 'D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.json' | Out-Null\n392: ```\n393: \n394: ## Translation Requirements\n395: \n396: - Preserve source behavior rather than file names alone.\n397: - Use source project structure as a responsibility guide while adapting to\n398:   HarmonyOS Cangjie idioms: keep domain/service/state boundaries clear, merge\n399:   source fragments when Cangjie reads better, and avoid overgrown all-purpose\n400:   files.\n401: - Recreate UI layout, navigation, validation, state refresh, transitions, loading/empty/error states, and user-visible side effects as closely as practical.\n402: - Translate resources and resource usages into HarmonyOS Cangjie style resources.\n403: - Copy image assets when valid; convert vector/state drawables or ArkTS resource references into usable HarmonyOS assets or Cangjie state code.\n404: - Replace unsupported Android, Jetpack, Firebase, Google, ArkTS-only, or third-party APIs with HarmonyOS/Cangjie APIs, Kits, packages, or compatible abstractions after checking docs/examples. Use local simulation only when no suitable platform or package capability exists and record the blocker.\n405: - Preserve backend, persistence, CRUD, refresh, observer/recomposition/state semantics recorded in analysis inputs.\n406: - Keep implementation modular; do not collapse the app into one large file.\n407: - Leave future integration points for platform services when local replacements are used.\n408: - Check that the program state machine is still satisfied at the end of each phase.\n409: - Preserve Kotlin app behavior, not just file names or UI appearance.\n410: - Preserve Jetpack Compose behavior when present: composables, state hoisting, remembered state, callbacks, navigation routes, screen parameters, LazyColumn/LazyRow behavior, filtering, search, validation, dialogs, bottom bars, and recomposition-triggering state changes.\n411: - Preserve XML/ViewBinding behavior when present: Activity/Fragment flow, adapters, click listeners, form validation, RecyclerView/ListView refresh behavior, and navigation.\n412: - Preserve ViewModel, StateFlow, LiveData, coroutine, repository, Room, Retrofit, Firebase, DataStore, SharedPreferences, and local cache semantics when present.\n413: - Translate Android resource definitions and Kotlin resource usages into HarmonyOS Cangjie style resources.\n414: - Copy image assets when direct copying is valid.\n415: - Convert Android vector or state drawable resources to usable HarmonyOS assets or Cangjie state code.\n416: - Replace unsupported Android SDK, Firebase SDK, Google SDK, Jetpack, or third-party dependencies with local or HarmonyOS-compatible abstractions.\n417: - Preserve backend, persistence, CRUD, refresh, observable state, and user-visible update semantics recorded in behavior specs.\n418: - For state mutation operations such as add/delete/update/search/filter, ensure the translated Cangjie UI immediately re-renders in the same situations where the Kotlin app recomposes, collects a new Flow value, observes LiveData, or refreshes an adapter.\n419: \n420: ## Test Migration Requirements\n421: \n422: - During planning, inspect the source project for tests such as `src/test`, `src/androidTest`, `test`, `tests`, `ohosTest`, or project-specific verification assets.\n423: - If the source project has tests, migrate or adapt the relevant tests into the target project so they validate translated Cangjie behavior rather than source-platform implementation details.\n424: - If the source project has no tests, generate a modest set of focused target-side tests for core behavior that can be tested without fragile UI automation, such as models, parsers, repositories, settings/preferences, CRUD, search/filtering, validation, state refresh, and important business rules.\n425: - If the source project has too few or shallow tests, add supplemental tests for high-risk translated behavior and any phase-critical data/state logic.\n426: - Prefer automated tests integrated with the target HarmonyOS Cangjie project. If the available SDK/project template does not support a runnable automated test for a behavior, keep the implementation testable, record the limitation, and add the smallest useful test harness or test specification inside the target project.\n427: - Do not delete or disable migrated/generated tests merely to make the build pass. If a test cannot be supported in the current phase, record it as deferred with source evidence, reason, fallback validation, and future completion path.\n428: - Report migrated tests, generated tests, supplemental tests, test commands run, and any deferred test coverage at the end of each phase.\n429: \n430: ## Build Gate Requirement\n431: \n432: After each implementation phase, run the full build gate via:\n433: \n434: ```bash\n435: C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py \\\n436:   --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike \\\n437:   --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony \\\n438:   --phase <phase-name>\n439: ```\n440: \n441: If the build gate fails, read the generated `build-report.md` and `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt`, then fix only the current phase blocker before continuing.\n442: \n443: ## Session Discipline\n444: \n445: - Always read the agent protocol before editing.\n446: - Always read `plan.md` and `plan.json` before phase work.\n447: - Do not modify `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`.\n448: - Do not modify `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-records`, workflow scripts, or generated reports other than the agent-maintained source coverage matrix and platform capability check.\n449: - If `apply_patch` fails, read back affected files before retrying.\n450: - At phase end, review contradictions with `plan.md` / `plan.json`, remove unnecessary temporary code, and record deferred issues.\n\n(End of file - total 450 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Translation Plan\n\n## Goal\n\nTranslate the Android Kotlin project in `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike` into a HarmonyOS Cangjie project rooted at `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`, preserving main features, screen flow, resources, state changes, data behavior, tests, and user-visible side effects while adapting implementation to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n\n## Paths\n\n- App name: `Foodike`\n- Source kind: `kotlin`\n- Translation workspace: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike`\n- Workspace standing instructions: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\AGENTS.md`\n- Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n- Target HarmonyOS Cangjie project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n- Translation inputs: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs`\n- Translation records: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-records`\n- Agent protocol: `D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md`\n- HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist: `D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\docs\\harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md`\n\n## Role Split","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"task-planning.md","time":{"start":1782533580761,"end":1782533580767}},"id":"prt_f0747e7ae001MQZGQ6KqkvtH0G","sessionID":"ses_0f8b84a87ffeugHsJw5ZQ49CGn","messageID":"msg_f0747d889001GggK5NbhCTyzD1"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782533580921,"sessionID":"ses_0f8b84a87ffeugHsJw5ZQ49CGn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_AIzZEqWMbpdYm1LOb5sih5IZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md"},"output":"<path>D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Foodike Translation Plan\n2: \n3: ## Scope And Evidence\n4: \n5: - Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n6: - Target project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n7: - Planning evidence: `translation-inputs/plan-seed.md`, `translation-inputs/plan-seed.json`, `translation-inputs/source-feature-survey.md`, `translation-inputs/source-coverage-matrix.json`, `translation-inputs/platform-capability-check.json`, `translation-inputs/android-analysis/behavior-spec.md`, `translation-inputs/resource-coverage-report.md`, `translation-inputs/coverage-gap-report.md`, `translation-inputs/target-structure-report.md`\n8: - Source inspection used to confirm behavior beyond static hints: `presentation/MainActivity.kt`, `presentation/common/SplashViewModel.kt`, `presentation/util/Navigation.kt`, `presentation/onboarding/OnBoarding.kt`, `presentation/login/LoginScreen.kt`, `presentation/home/HomeScreen.kt`, `presentation/history/History.kt`, `presentation/details/RestaurantDetail.kt`, `presentation/cart/Cart.kt`, `presentation/profile/Profile.kt`, `presentation/*ViewModel.kt`, `data/repository/*.kt`, `README.md`\n9: \n10: ## Source Behavior Summary\n11: \n12: Foodike is a single-activity Jetpack Compose app with MVVM-style state and fake local repositories. Startup uses splash gating plus persisted login state to choose onboarding or home. Navigation includes onboarding, login, home, history, cart, profile, and restaurant detail routes, with a conditional bottom bar plus central cart FAB on home/history. Home renders greeting, search, ads, recommended foods, favourite restaurants, chip filters, and restaurant cards; selecting a restaurant writes it into shared repository state before navigating. Detail consumes repository state to show the selected restaurant, recommended/non-veg/veg collapsible sections, like toggle, share affordance, and cart shortcut when any item count is non-zero. History reuses search plus tabs over liked restaurants. Cart shows selected items, coupon, delivery, and bill sections. Profile shows static user info, profile actions, and logout. Login validates hard-coded credentials, persists login state through DataStore, and uses snackbar errors for invalid input. Recomposition is driven by mutable Compose state and Flow collection in ViewModels and repositories, so immediate UI updates after repository mutation are part of required parity.\n13: \n14: ## Planning Baseline\n15: \n16: - `source-feature-survey.md` reports 224 critical/high feature rows and 6 unresolved critical/high platform capabilities.\n17: - `resource-coverage-report.md` reports 52 source strings versus 31 target strings, so resource parity needs an explicit early phase.\n18: - `coverage-gap-report.md` reports target production code LoC below source and warns about uncovered feature rows and unresolved platform capabilities.\n19: - `target-structure-report.md` shows current target architecture already has app/data/features folders, but `bootstrap_page.cj` and `features/home/home_page.cj` are concentration risks and should not absorb unrelated behavior.\n20: \n21: ## Target Architecture Direction\n22: \n23: Use the current target module layout as the base and keep responsibilities clear:\n24: \n25: - `app/`: bootstrap state, startup route selection, root router, shell composition\n26: - `data/content/`: fake content catalogs, repository implementations, resource-backed sample data, search/filter helpers\n27: - `data/session/`: login/session persistence, selected restaurant state, liked/cart state storage\n28: - `domain/`: domain models and service contracts shaped after source repositories and screen state needs\n29: - `features/startup/`: splash and start-destination selection\n30: - `features/onboarding/`, `login/`, `home/`, `history/`, `detail/`, `cart/`, `profile/`: page composition, screen-local state adapters, focused widgets\n31: - `common/`: shared widgets, resource adapters, formatting helpers\n32: \n33: Do not close broad source behavior through only `bootstrap_page.cj` or one broad state file. Screen and repository behaviors should land in precise feature or data modules.\n34: \n35: ## Phases\n36: \n37: ### Phase 01: Project Skeleton And Resource Parity\n38: \n39: - Goal: stabilize target app entry, startup route shell, domain package anchors, and resource coverage so later behavior work does not hard-code strings or overload shell pages.\n40: - Depends on: existing target skeleton only.\n41: - Key source evidence:\n42:   - `app/src/main/AndroidManifest.xml`\n43:   - `app/src/main/res/values/strings.xml`\n44:   - `app/src/main/res/values/colors.xml`\n45:   - `app/src/main/res/values/themes.xml`\n46:   - `README.md` screenshots and screen list\n47: - Required target focus:\n48:   - Confirm route ids and bootstrap shell match source screen inventory.\n49:   - Expand string/color/media assets coverage for onboarding, login, home, history, detail, cart, and profile labels.\n50:   - Split or guard concentrated shell surfaces before later phase expansion.\n51: - Gate:\n52:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`\n53: - Expected evidence:\n54:   - Build gate pass.\n55:   - Resource files and route shell endpoints exist under feature/common modules.\n56:   - No new shell concentration beyond current warnings.\n57: \n58: ### Phase 02: Startup, Session Persistence, Navigation, And Shared Data Contracts\n59: \n60: - Goal: implement startup routing, login-state persistence, shared selected-restaurant/cart/favourites state, repository contracts, and navigation shell behavior that other screens depend on.\n61: - Depends on: phase 01 resources and route shell.\n62: - Key source evidence:\n63:   - `presentation/MainActivity.kt`\n64:   - `presentation/common/SplashViewModel.kt`\n65:   - `presentation/util/Navigation.kt`\n66:   - `domain/repository/LoginRepository.kt`\n67:   - `data/repository/LoginRepositoryImpl.kt`\n68:   - `domain/repository/HomeRepository.kt`\n69:   - `domain/repository/UserDataRepository.kt`\n70:   - `data/repository/HomeRepositoryImpl.kt`\n71:   - `data/repository/UserDataRepositoryImpl.kt`\n72: - Required target focus:\n73:   - Preserve start destination semantics: onboarding when logged out, home when logged in.\n74:   - Persist session state with HarmonyOS-compatible preferences/storage.\n75:   - Preserve repository-driven immediate updates after `setRestaurant`, login toggle, liked/cart stream reads, and menu retrieval.\n76:   - Preserve bottom bar and cart FAB visibility rules for home/history.\n77:   - Establish target endpoints precise enough for later matrix closure.\n78: - Gate:\n79:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-02-startup-session-navigation`\n80: - Expected evidence:\n81:   - Build gate pass.\n82:   - Focused tests for session persistence and repository mutation/refresh behavior where harness allows.\n83: \n84: ### Phase 03: Onboarding And Login Flow\n85: \n86: - Goal: migrate onboarding pager flow and login UI/validation/session handoff.\n87: - Depends on: phase 02 shared navigation and session persistence.\n88: - Key source evidence:\n89:   - `presentation/onboarding/OnBoarding.kt`\n90:   - `presentation/onboarding/components/OnboardingPage.kt`\n91:   - `presentation/onboarding/util/OnBoardingItem.kt`\n92:   - `presentation/login/LoginScreen.kt`\n93:   - `presentation/login/LoginViewModel.kt`\n94:   - `presentation/login/components/FoodikeTextField.kt`\n95: - Required target focus:\n96:   - Preserve multi-page onboarding progression and final navigation to login.\n97:   - Preserve login text entry state, hard-coded credential check, snackbar error, and successful transition to home with session toggle.\n98:   - Preserve coming-soon affordances for social login and ancillary actions unless product decides otherwise.\n99: - Gate:\n100:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-03-onboarding-login`\n101: - Expected evidence:\n102:   - Build gate pass.\n103:   - Focused tests for credential validation and session toggle path where possible.\n104:   - Manual review note for onboarding pager progression if automated UI coverage is unavailable.\n105: \n106: ### Phase 04: Home And History Discovery Flows\n107: \n108: - Goal: migrate feed/list discovery, search/filter affordances, favourites/history flows, and route-to-detail selection behavior.\n109: - Depends on: phase 02 shared repositories and phase 03 authenticated entry.\n110: - Key source evidence:\n111:   - `presentation/home/HomeScreen.kt`\n112:   - `presentation/home/HomeViewModel.kt`\n113:   - `presentation/home/HomeScreenState.kt`\n114:   - `presentation/home/components/*.kt`\n115:   - `presentation/components/SearchBar.kt`\n116:   - `presentation/components/RestaurantCard.kt`\n117:   - `presentation/history/History.kt`\n118:   - `presentation/history/HistoryViewModel.kt`\n119:   - `presentation/history/components/*.kt`\n120: - Required target focus:\n121:   - Preserve home section ordering, conditional favourite section, and restaurant selection semantics.\n122:   - Preserve search/filter chip interactions and list refresh behavior.\n123:   - Preserve history tabs and liked restaurant navigation back into detail using repository selection.\n124:   - Keep bottom bar/cart FAB behavior aligned with the source shell.\n125: - Gate:\n126:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-04-home-history`\n127: - Expected evidence:\n128:   - Build gate pass.\n129:   - Focused tests for repository-backed restaurant selection, favourites stream updates, and search/filter helpers.\n130: \n131: ### Phase 05: Detail And Cart Mutation Flows\n132: \n133: - Goal: migrate restaurant detail, expandable menu sections, like/cart state, and cart summary flow.\n134: - Depends on: phase 02 shared repository state and phase 04 selection flows.\n135: - Key source evidence:\n136:   - `presentation/details/RestaurantDetail.kt`\n137:   - `presentation/details/RestaurantDetailViewModel.kt`\n138:   - `presentation/details/DetailScreenState.kt`\n139:   - `presentation/details/components/*.kt`\n140:   - `presentation/cart/Cart.kt`\n141:   - `presentation/cart/CartViewModel.kt`\n142:   - `presentation/cart/CartState.kt`\n143:   - `presentation/cart/components/*.kt`\n144:   - `data/repository/UserDataRepositoryImpl.kt`\n145: - Required target focus:\n146:   - Preserve selected restaurant display and menu grouping into recommended/non-veg/veg sections.\n147:   - Preserve expandable section state and immediate recomposition on toggle.\n148:   - Preserve like toggle semantics, cart FAB visibility, cart item count filtering, coupon/delivery/bill sections, and navigation back behavior.\n149:   - Replace any source placeholder mutation gaps with explicit target commands that keep intended user-visible behavior coherent.\n150: - Gate:\n151:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-05-detail-cart`\n152: - Expected evidence:\n153:   - Build gate pass.\n154:   - Focused tests for section toggles, menu partitioning helpers, and cart summary math/state where possible.\n155: \n156: ### Phase 06: Profile, Capability Resolution, And Verification Hardening\n157: \n158: - Goal: finish profile/logout flow, close remaining resource/capability decisions, and add focused target-side verification for core state/data behaviors.\n159: - Depends on phases 01-05.\n160: - Key source evidence:\n161:   - `presentation/profile/Profile.kt`\n162:   - `presentation/profile/ProfileViewModel.kt`\n163:   - `app/src/test/java/com/example/foodike/ExampleUnitTest.kt`\n164:   - `app/src/androidTest/java/com/example/foodike/ExampleInstrumentedTest.kt`\n165:   - `translation-inputs/platform-capability-check.json`\n166: - Required target focus:\n167:   - Preserve logout flow back to onboarding and any profile action placeholders with clear product-level handling.\n168:   - Resolve or explicitly defer the six platform capabilities with evidence, not local simulation as final capability closure.\n169:   - Add focused tests for startup routing, repository state streams, login persistence, selection propagation, and screen-local reducer logic.\n170:   - Prepare row-level records follow-up after the plan contract passes.\n171: - Gate:\n172:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-06-profile-capabilities-verification`\n173: - Expected evidence:\n174:   - Build gate pass.\n175:   - Test compile/run evidence for focused target tests where supported.\n176:   - Capability notes updated with doc/package evidence during implementation sessions.\n177: \n178: ## Test Strategy\n179: \n180: - Source tests are only template examples and do not cover real app behavior.\n181: - Add target-side focused tests for:\n182:   - startup destination selection from persisted session state\n183:   - login credential validation and logout/session mutation\n184:   - repository data retrieval and selected restaurant propagation\n185:   - favourites/cart/menu stream refresh semantics\n186:   - search/filter and detail-section partition helpers\n187: - When full target test execution is blocked by SDK or harness limits, keep testable pure modules and record exact harness blockers instead of leaving only placeholder test files.\n188: \n189: ## Platform Capability Review Plan\n190: \n191: - `media-library-access`: review whether current target only needs bundled images or also user media selection; if user media is required, resolve with HarmonyOS picker/media APIs behind a service boundary.\n192: - `file-access-and-saf`: inspect whether any source share/import/export behavior is real versus seed over-detection; if no real source flow exists, narrow via source override during implementation records.\n193: - `image-viewer-gestures`: confirm whether source really has zoom/gallery behavior or only static image cards; prefer source override if static only, otherwise plan a reusable image viewer surface.\n194: - `localization-resources`: critical for current plan due to string coverage gap.\n195: - `runtime-permissions`: likely over-detected for much of the app because the inspected source files do not request permissions directly; verify before closing capability rows.\n196: - `background-and-platform-components`: likely limited to splash and app entry for this sample; verify before treating as a large deferred area.\n197: \n198: ## Analysis Gaps And Source Overrides To Track\n199: \n200: - `plan-seed.md` reports missing-analysis warnings for files that are actually present in the workspace. Treat that as stale generated metadata rather than absence of evidence.\n201: - Seed/platform hints over-flag file access, media library, image viewer gestures, runtime permissions, and background components across many files. Implementation sessions must confirm these from source before closing capability rows or planning a large replacement.\n202: - The source app itself contains placeholders or shallow behaviors, especially social login, profile action cards, share button, and cart increment/decrement callbacks. Preserve current user-visible semantics, but do not invent backend completeness without explicit product direction.\n203: \n204: ## Deferred Risks\n205: \n206: - Capability rows may shrink after source confirmation; until then they remain planning risks rather than confirmed implementation scope.\n207: - Current target string coverage is incomplete and risks silent UX drift if resource parity is not addressed first.\n208: - The current target shell already concentrates multiple routes in `bootstrap_page.cj`; expanding features there would make later coverage repair harder.\n209: - Automated UI verification may be limited; if so, behavior proof must rely on focused tests plus documented manual review targets.\n210: \n211: ## Post-Planning Follow-Up\n212: \n213: - Do not perform broad `plannedPhase` backfill during this session.\n214: - After this plan contract is accepted, run a narrow records-only backfill session to map matrix rows and platform capability rows to the phase/group ids defined in `plan.json`.\n\n(End of file - total 214 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Foodike Translation Plan\n\n## Scope And Evidence\n\n- Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n- Target project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n- Planning evidence: `translation-inputs/plan-seed.md`, `translation-inputs/plan-seed.json`, `translation-inputs/source-feature-survey.md`, `translation-inputs/source-coverage-matrix.json`, `translation-inputs/platform-capability-check.json`, `translation-inputs/android-analysis/behavior-spec.md`, `translation-inputs/resource-coverage-report.md`, `translation-inputs/coverage-gap-report.md`, `translation-inputs/target-structure-report.md`\n- Source inspection used to confirm behavior beyond static hints: `presentation/MainActivity.kt`, `presentation/common/SplashViewModel.kt`, `presentation/util/Navigation.kt`, `presentation/onboarding/OnBoarding.kt`, `presentation/login/LoginScreen.kt`, `presentation/home/HomeScreen.kt`, `presentation/history/History.kt`, `presentation/details/RestaurantDetail.kt`, `presentation/cart/Cart.kt`, `presentation/profile/Profile.kt`, `presentation/*ViewModel.kt`, `data/repository/*.kt`, `README.md`\n\n## Source Behavior Summary\n\nFoodike is a single-activity Jetpack Compose app with MVVM-style state and fake local repositories. Startup uses splash gating plus persisted login state to choose onboarding or home. Navigation includes onboarding, login, home, history, cart, profile, and restaurant detail routes, with a conditional bottom bar plus central cart FAB on home/history. Home renders greeting, search, ads, recommended foods, favourite restaurants, chip filters, and restaurant cards; selecting a restaurant writes it into shared repository state before navigating. Detail consumes repository state to show the selected restaurant, recommended/non-veg/veg collapsible sections, like toggle, share affordance, and cart shortcut when any item count is non-zero. History reuses search plus tabs over liked restaurants. Cart shows selected items, coupon, delivery, and bill sections. Profile shows static user info, profile actions, and logout. Login validates hard-coded credentials, persists login state through DataStore, and uses snackbar errors for invalid input. Recomposition is driven by mutable Compose state and Flow collection in ViewModels and repositories, so immediate UI updates after repository mutation are part of required parity.\n\n## Planning Baseline\n\n- `source-feature-survey.md` reports 224 critical/high feature rows and 6 unresolved critical/high platform capabilities.\n- `resource-coverage-report.md` reports 52 source strings versus 31 target strings, so resource parity needs an explicit early phase.\n- `coverage-gap-report.md` reports target production code LoC below source and warns about uncovered feature rows and unresolved platform capabilities.\n- `target-structure-report.md` shows current target architecture already has app/data/features folders, but `bootstrap_page.cj` and `features/home/home_page.cj` are concentration risks and should not absorb unrelated behavior.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"plan.md","time":{"start":1782533580915,"end":1782533580920}},"id":"prt_f0747e7db001P4epnjlg4mwSHH","sessionID":"ses_0f8b84a87ffeugHsJw5ZQ49CGn","messageID":"msg_f0747d889001GggK5NbhCTyzD1"}}
